This paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category as it deals with mechanism design, which is a central topic in game theory. It also involves the study of equilibria in distribution-committing games, which is a common approach in game theory. The sub-category of Economics and Computation (cs.EC) is also likely as it deals with the design and analysis of algorithms for economic systems. The sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) is relevant as it involves the study of algorithms and their efficiency, which is important in mechanism design. The sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) is relevant as it involves the study of intelligent agents and their decision-making processes, which is relevant in mechanism design. Finally, the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) is relevant as it involves the study of secure mechanisms and protocols, which is important in mechanism design to prevent manipulation and fraud.
